A Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policy with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, confirming that the US election fraud is rarer than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, in 10 years in the United States, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that make it difficult for registration or urning.
After the November 2010 elections, this phenomenon has gained in importance, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states being registered.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo identification and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare the right invalid to register as voters on the electoral day, and decree citizens the right to vote for which a court act exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. State required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Act of Indiana.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the past two years, they have promoted laws in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible persons do not have a photo identification issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an ID card.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to obtain the necessary ID card.
Of the new restrictions, young people, minorities and low-income people are disproportionately affected.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with a income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years do not have the necessary photo identification.
This is still enough.
Students who are considered voters, who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more strongly for the Republican side to use the tickets issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state for the election required proof of citizenship.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting hispanic votes.
Because it is obvious that two of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted eight federal states to abolish the registration of voters on the electoral day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaign to register voters during the 2004 general elections contributed to the registration of approximately 10 million citizens.
Because the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the share of registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, which represented 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who were elected in advance.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their followers have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The United States Advocate General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo identification.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
The democratic critics advocate the political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the countries issuing the 2012 issue.
A report by the Brennan Center of 2011 shows that those states that have passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral body to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these amendments to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on electoral participation.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the US democratic system.
