The Higgs Boson Analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a certain sensation last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this Boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
Finally, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but was not yet observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let's assume that this is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what it is all about.
There is a necessarily indispensable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and don't try it too hard, as you are going to hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantity state", with this "state" largely consisting of some of their characteristics.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, who are similar to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil band of anarchists who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they may indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These Bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure from the Berkeley laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing): the Mesons we are not treated here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs Boson would be somehow related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a bosoon of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bod" of electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this place, like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disorder" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of power".
Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this Boson shows itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen has to achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a range of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, there are not all particles and not all the materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (as well as the photon) do not have any mass.
For what can all these research now be "good," asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to investigate in detail all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not explain gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renewed ups!).
However, no such deviations have been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no such thing.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was considered at the beginning rather as a "laboratory play".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras worldwide and has presented him with the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
Quebec has recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its Committee on "Death in Dignity".
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important subject area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that devoured him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I made seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the house for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he wants to resign to help himself with food.
He even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our life, we learn that a man is pinging in the standing," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist in the home of Victor-Gadbois.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the ability of the person," he notes.
In the view of several people working in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these steps.
The patients who are forced into the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
You have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer deal with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But because of the illness, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the next few days, she still expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is offered with a group of voluntary personal care and assistance in food intake.
The palliative care is then used if there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec a bed for palliative care comes to 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if you take into account that one day we'll all die.
Here life will continue under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on the wish, the dying person is granted oral care with Brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help family and patients alike," reports Care Director Nathalie Savard.
In the home Victor-Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while one is indulging in his honor, a young man of 36 years dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"Since six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel said alarmedly.
53% of patients admitted to the home Victor-Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians have no access to palliative care, i.e. to care that should relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the home palliative care society in Montreal, are more or less specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec's health care that makes sure that several doctors specialised in palliative care face the adoption of a law on the control of death and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent figures of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health system is not capable enough to ensure that all the right to high-quality palliative care is maintained before accepting death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room 14 days with great pain, without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients will die only because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of worst forecasts until the last day.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were minimal when she discontinued a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry I gave up the fight, she told me.
However, she told me I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not allowing this desire after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the society of the home palliative care of the Greater Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the end of life, the doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which is aimed at sleeping either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer do as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to access this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not eased all say the same sentence, "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain to be eased."
