Each year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families remaining in their home country.
On 1 December, a law came into force that requires every migrant worker to take a test that confirms knowledge of Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants wishing to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, the tests will in future become mandatory for all host workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
In doing so, one must not only take language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the maintenance and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is an official language.
It also excludes persons who have received their certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The total number of examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the representatives of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the law entered into force in the press, citizens asked the following question several times: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement of having to show language skills, both for the Russians and for the host workers?
