"In your home country, you will be promised the One, and on arrival you will cheat, get their passports removed and do not receive the promised wage," confirms the Head of the Labour Migration Administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripow.
Don't yell, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian Republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that not only do they not control the language of the target country, but they can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbekistan and Tajiks can afford reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school items.
As a teenager these children then immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It is difficult without language knowledge," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
With regard to the law, civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers continue to reside illegally in Russia.
"Welcome warmly" or "Access for unauthorized persons forbidden"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for a thousand and a half.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and that is why cases of extortion arise.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tadskike Umed Huschkadamov to journalists.
"Do not stifle any costs for false papers"
Already on the day when the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be fake.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for nothing: Every migrants who hoped to be able to save themselves the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
In addition, the main direct task of protecting the system from corruption is to ensure that certificates cannot be bought easily, both officials and citizens agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who first fall through the test that they will receive time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
