At the meeting of the Chamber of Deputies' Control Committee, you discussed a joint Czech-German project in which the laws of both countries relating to public contracts were compared.
What exactly was that about?
This is a parallel examination which we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is about the European legislation defining how public procurement can be handled, on which national legislation builds, and finally there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we have been able to determine extremely interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws in us are perhaps even a little "harder and more perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to set new and more precise rules over and over again. It is also necessary to deal with the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results from this project?
Such a joint control could help us to stop trying constantly to perfect the laws and reduce and elucidate thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economics means buying a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding illegal enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of thresholds for contracts does not guarantee that we also achieve this objective.
It may even be that we only burden the system with excessive "paperwork" in this way, and those looking for gaps in the system have much easier use of the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
