Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think is going to happen in less than a month of the world's downfall?
This is one of those news of disasters that we people are so happy to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we're rather making fun of it and saying that we're the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the world's downfall.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the global downfall.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a national benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this purpose, we want to use the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, which is forecast to be at 11:10 a.m. at the end of December 21st.
On the day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava will be held at the same time as from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is to be in about the time when the Maya calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
Who's that idea from?
Originally probably from me, after that we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Hanza Augusta.
Not only do we want to collect enough positive energy to prevent world ruin, we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we hand over this world to our children.
At the end of the Maya calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the global downfall, with which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded together with other performers the so-called hymn against the world's downfall entitled "World Fall Out".
Already today the hymn on YouTube is very popular. Will it also sound like the benefit concerts?
Of course, in conclusion, provided that everything works and the world does not happen...
The hymn is to be sung at the same time by all performers on all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live in a direct circuit from Czech television.
The text of the hymn comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X sings with...
How did you get to work with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the global downfall?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the Association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly cared for by readers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the readers, we want to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, we are expected to create our own building, in which we will then move in with this project.
At each concert several groups and performers perform.
Which criteria have you chosen?
We wanted to put together a program that addresses all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbias, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango, and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "great events" also planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and we will also prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to be at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you handle these trips logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair drivers, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage room. In addition, of course, we have to drag a lot of instrument case and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have wondered in part.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we were just in Russia witnesses that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
About Prague, Moscow is absolutely unobstructed, where it is still unusual when someone is traveling in the wheelchair alone in the city center.
It's not even obvious there that you're leaving a wheelchair driver in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations who are trying to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we need to catch up with the developed countries?
There's still a lot of things we're hanging out in...
However, it should be noted that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in the social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly willful personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to create a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone among other things, I have founded a music-AG together with a colleague.
Well, and in time, as our moderator, Láða Angelovič, used to say, something out of control (laughs).
