Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to a Council of Ministers meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA) as the 20th member of this space authority. Poland is the second member country from the former eastern block (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland into space obviously began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were already engaged in space, and they did not always come to understand it.
For example, I am reminded of the presentation by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneer work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-renowned contribution to the development of space was honoured, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the face of the moon was named after him.
In 1925, a railway-draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket-powered engine was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the draisine.
The information is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research carried out by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the documents submitted that research had been carried out to the stage of practical tests.
The research was of course interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the technical press appeared in the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket from Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" was published by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects were concerned with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all the projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polishe Towarzystwo Astronautczne).
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space society.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was a good idea that the exploration of space would have the future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Society PTA sought to join the International Space Federation, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member already in autumn 1956.
The following year the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed chairman of the International Space Federation.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the highly successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 a flight test with the two-step rocket RM-2 began in the Błődów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was halted.
The first rocket of the type RM was replaced by the meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed of this rocket (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a transport room with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COPPAR (Commission for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a National COPPAR Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second interkosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
