In November 1979, a Mob of protesting Islamic students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the USA after the revolution, who had kept the Patronate over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, since this would have caused massive damage to the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the call of the united states, and the subsequent Fiasco in the violent attempt of hostage liberation made everything worse.
Finally, after 444 days of negotiations by the Algerian government, the diplomats were released.
The fate of the hostages caused at home a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo of the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the message, six ambassadors managed to flee.
It ended after numerous complications at the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In cooperation with the Canadian authorities, the CIA succeeded in bringing refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to hide their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports camouflaged as members of a film staff who supposedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of the genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltation", Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
In order to make the camouflage credible, articles on this film project appeared in technical journals, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
Thus, the levels of mood change in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the looser passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly overstretched.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the office floor, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable re-start of his career with this film.
From a smiled actor he has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is now no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime No children's game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without grace (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film that doesn't play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the first storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, but nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck also has a similar effect with his team in fictitious scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that history does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping reality a little - which does not always work so elegantly (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is turned off by a telephone call in America, or also the pursuit of the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide scatter, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their figures deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thus loses a bit of tensile strength. It is a film that can be followed with a certain interest and the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70th years.
However, he is very much invigorating.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history still alive in a certain way and as evidence of how the notions of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services were overlaid, he is sufficient.
