Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany has abstained in the vote on the reception of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-European relations, Berlin thus balances at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the application for an observer status of the Palestinians in the United Nations.
But then there was Berlin.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Germany must be careful due to its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to setting up a flight ban zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely changing its foreign policy away from a policy, which was, so to speak, managed by the US, towards a German foreign policy.
Furthermore, it is difficult for Europeans not to have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they still have a bearing on their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy as they have France or the UK.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from the point of view of Germany?
It shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. from exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the attitude of the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to hit the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight either, that's not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from the vote on important decisions, for example in the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the USA there is great understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even play a certain role in this respect.
After all, it signals that as an international player it must be taken seriously and its interests should be considered.
There are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that under Obama, the government may secretly have a lot of understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I think that the actual disagreements are not as big as they always appear.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanjahu, Obama is not so excited about Netanya's politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree its close relations with Israel and the USA on the one hand, and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a wider line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe into a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I believe that the Germans are aware that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself in the role as an important international player - does Germany want to play a major role at all?
Or does Germany still have a hard lead role to play?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a bigger role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, then every time Germany takes on a larger role, various anti-German feelings become free.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Thus, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be receptive to different neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European policy is constantly decreasing, but the EU is currently filling this vacuum, who else is there?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant and it makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America are jointly researching the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
