Facts on sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papilomaviruses, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Filzlauze and scratches belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and trippers occur especially in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of the syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contacts between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonades, candiosis (pilz), tripper and human papilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is relatively low - nevertheless, about 20 percent of HIV new infections are related to this group.
Among adolescents, Chlamydia infections occur much more frequently than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
Human papilomaviruses are also common in young people in this area.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011.
The number of HIV new infections has declined since 2007.
In 2011, there were some 2,700 cases.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What are some symptoms of sexual illness?
The infectious diseases may cause ulcers in the genital area, problems in urinating, exodus, lower abdominal pain, bladders or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condomes can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100% protection.
In part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close contact with the body.
Therefore, experts especially recommend regular studies in frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosed, most STIs can be cured and later avoided.
