On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not mine, or someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, nudes, crimes, or to write abusive or violent comments.
Jorge guarantees to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just uploading them up," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can speak quickly with relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
He answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone recommended a stranger to him, he would ignore this.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask he admits not to know 20 of the people he has added to his list of friends.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one made any indications or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If someone pressures me or asks them for me, I simply remove him from my user account," he admits.
José reported to Ask after reading a recommendation in Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences that are known today as cyberbullying.
The acquaintance of a friend was blackmailed in a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He just made it private."
He then explains a number of steps to safely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if he was unsympathetic with me or if I wanted to wipe him out.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
