Completion of the Unasur Summit without publication of Lima's declaration
The 6th summit of the Presidents of the Union of South America (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially announced that they would hand it over after the clause, but then declared that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian government.
In the case of questions on the text, they indicated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day in the press room, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted with the message "Private Session, Limited Audio".
The few information that circulated among journalists was received by the press representatives of some of the Unasur's governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press speaker.
The only document that was disseminated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
The President of Peru then sent an e-mail to the media with the "Declaration" of the Summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document for the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru was host to the IIIrd Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite the press's strong call, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced before, was neither published.
On the official website of ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but to a large extent limited access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH that began in The Hague on Monday, in the trial that Lima launched against Santiago, to hear the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the ruling on the differences we are currently making to this international court," said Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, and continues to be, a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would submit to the IGH was made after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, had filed an action against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present.
Paraguay, who has been excluded from Unasur since 2011, did not take part in the meeting after the resignation of his President Fernando Lugo.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks on the morning and ended the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document stating that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were established over an investment of a total of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He stated that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not take on triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our people a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects, which should improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian president in a read-only statement.
These projects would also include five Peruvians lying on the transverse axes of their territory from the coast to Brazil, two of which should provide better links with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will be used for its resumption in the Union of South American nations", which it is currently excluded from.
The need for Latin America to continue to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and for good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was stressed at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting, that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to deal respectfully with the maritime conflict after a judgment of the IGH, which Bogotá called into question.
"Maybe I'll meet President Daniel Ortega on the morning (Saturday)," said Santos.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and respectfully as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the office of the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nito.
As part of the summit, the Ministers for Defence of the Block met in advance to adopt the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even though the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru has the presidency at the time of the regional block.
