Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Hector "Hetin" Reyes, the world drummer of basketball, was connected to basket sports for more than 60 years and has traveled all over the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a great spiritual collection of the history of basketball in the country as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before he was tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, players of the first national league, authorised and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"For my life, I have put up many hats in basketball, even several at the same time as I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 1990s," Reyes remembered when he visited Primera Hora at home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes doesn't overdo this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to it.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, where he celebrated his 15-year anniversary as co-business leader or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years, which I enjoyed most, because I was allowed to be part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967 as managing director, co-business leader or coach.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I agreed with a 1981 championship, the year of the debut of Jerome Mincy at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who worked as a coach here and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said, "I have a very strong and 2 m big player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who was a citizen and one of our best pitchers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would take care of another one.
The Vaqueros championship with Gausse was awarded to him, but already out of a distance, because he was already in the top position of the association in 1988.
At that time he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the US.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze, if not that Canadian referee, who had us repeat the last turn for the second time, Reyes said.
Was that group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as is the one who won against the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
My favorite, however, is the team of the 1991 Pan-American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered a fight to the US team, as they won against us at the bronze World Cup.
In that team, not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and Piculín (Ortiz) were there again, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 because of a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy was that of the pre-olimpic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina in 1995.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a substitute for the locked players because of the occurrences at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any prognosis.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was without a doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His figures at the level of the international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Piculín.
And this without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best coach from Puerto Rico?
That is a difficult question.
We had a number of good trainers like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like Leo Arill's work.
What do you think is the best you've achieved in the union?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN from the beginning of the 90s to 17 teams in one season.
What else do you have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, play only in their territory and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, children make unnecessary travel and games.
At least I see the outcome of the required training courses and courses for trainers, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, see videos of music of my time in YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and from time to time I go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always at my side.
Larry Hagman is dead
Larry Hagman was born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth (Texas) and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R". in the television series "Dallas", where he played a unscrupulous, secretive and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birthplace of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," said the family.
The Larry family and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of the Feast of Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original and serial series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, said her publisher Jeffrey Lane.
He made everyone happy to know him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life in full swings," explained Gray in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed in 1992 with cirrhosis of the liver, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas", Hagman became known on TV as a nice type in 1965 to 1970 with the Sitcom "Beautiful Jeannie" of the TV station NBC.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on the head when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden) who will live with him at home.
He was also an actor of two comedies that were broadcast for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His cinematographic works included critically rated roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charming loathsome J.R. who made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television chain on the Ewing clan and other figures in its surroundings was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertisement "Who shot at J.R?", which was expected to create an episode full of emotions, where Hagmann's figure was almost killed, led to an international speculation, and millions of dollars were wagered in bethouses.
The series thus reached a record of audiences at the time.
When the answer became known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million spectators who turned "Dallas" into the second most widely seen entertainment program since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was Kristin who shot J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby).
